  "prompt": "Can cataracts affect younger people? What are the most common causes of it?",
  "response": "Yes, cataracts can affect younger people, although they are more commonly associated with older age. While cataracts are often linked to aging, various factors can contribute to their development in younger individuals.\n\n**Common Causes of Cataracts in Younger People:**\n1. **Congenital Factors**: Some infants are born with cataracts, a condition known as congenital cataracts, which can be due to genetic factors or maternal infections during pregnancy.\n  \n2. **Trauma**: Eye injuries can lead to cataracts, particularly if there is damage to the lens of the eye.\n\n3. **Medical Conditions**: Certain health issues, such as diabetes, can contribute to cataract formation at a younger age. Diabetes can lead to a specific type of cataract called diabetic cataract.\n\n4. **Medications**: Long-term use of corticosteroids and some other medications can increase the risk of developing cataracts.\n\n5. **Radiation Exposure**: Individuals who have undergone radiation therapy, particularly to the head or neck, are at increased risk for cataracts.\n\n6. **Lifestyle Factors**: Smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, and prolonged exposure to UV light without protection can also contribute to cataract development.\n\n7. **Systemic Diseases**: Conditions like galactosemia or atopic dermatitis may predispose individuals to cataracts.\n\nWhile less common, these factors illustrate that younger individuals can indeed develop cataracts, and awareness of the causes can facilitate early diagnosis and treatment. If there are concerns about vision changes or symptoms associated with cataracts, it\u2019s advisable to consult an eye care professional.",
